problem:
Do there exist primes $q, p_1, p_2$ and positive integers $m, n, \alpha_1, \alpha_2$ satisfying simultaneously:

(1) $q^{\alpha_1} \mid p_1^m - 1,\quad q^{\alpha_2} \mid p_2^m - 1,\quad m > 3n^2$;

(2) $p_1 < p_2 < p_1^{9/8},\quad q^{n\alpha_1} > p_1^{m-1},\quad q^{n\alpha_2} > p_2^{m-1}$?

There are several coins, each with a positive integer value, and the total value is $S$. Prove that there exists a positive integer $S_0$ such that whenever $S \ge S_0$, one can select some of the coins (possibly a single coin) and split them into several piles (possibly one pile) satisfying:

- Every pile contains the same number of coins, and that number does not exceed 100;
- All piles have the same total value;
- The total value of the selected coins is greater than $S^{0.98}$.

A circle $\omega$ touches a half-plane $H$ if $H$ does not contain $\omega$ and $\omega$ is tangent to the boundary line of $H$. Let $\mathcal{H}$ be a finite non-empty set of half-planes in a plane satisfying the following three conditions simultaneously:

1. The boundary lines of the half-planes in $\mathcal{H}$ are in general position (no two are parallel and no three are concurrent);
2. For any three half-planes in $\mathcal{H}$ there exists a circle touching them all;
3. No circle touches all half-planes in $\mathcal{H}$.

Prove that there exists a circle touching exactly three half-planes in $\mathcal{H}$.
